   Going by the file names only. I am guessing that {* /ai-code-exercises/use-cases/code-algorithms/javascript/TaskManager/app.js}[app.js] contins the bulk of the code logic. 
   This file is responsible for control flow of the program and bringing the different parts of the files together in a single coherent code flow.
   Furthermore,  I am thinking that {* /ai-code-exercises/use-cases/code-algorithms/javascript/TaskManager/cli.js}[cli.js] is responsible for collecting user input and and rendering output to standard out/in.
   I am also thinking that {* /ai-code-exercises/use-cases/code-algorithms/javascript/TaskManager/models.js}[models.js] contains the data structures. The data-transfer-objects of the program. It contains the structures that determine
   the shape of a `Task` and it's related methods. I guessing that {* /ai-code-exercises/use-cases/code-algorithms/javascript/TaskManager/storage.js}[storage.js] holds the logic for task persistence.
   After skimming through the file. I can tell that the program persists data to the filesystem. Looking at the {* /ai-code-exercises/use-cases/code-algorithms/javascript/TaskManager/README.md}[README.md], the program
   is used as follows: &node cli.js create <title> [options]&. So, for  {* /ai-code-exercises/use-cases/code-algorithms/javascript/TaskManager/task_list_merge.js}[task_list_merge.js] and {* /ai-code-exercises/use-cases/code-algorithms/javascript/TaskManager/task_parser.js}[task_parser.js], 
   I am guessing that the former holds logic on how to merge the different types of tasks that we can create with persisted tasks, while the later is used to parser user input 
   provided via the terminal. For example, &node cli.js create "Complete assessment one" -d "Finish the task manager project" -p 3 -u 2026-05-25 -t "work,coding,important"&, the *task_parser.js*
   would parse the all arguments after the `cli.js` into `Task`, `Tag`, and `Priority`, while the *task_list_merge.js* file adds/merge the new task with existing tasks. Testing of the varies APIs
   is done in the *test* folder.

** List the technologies and frameworks you think it uses
   The presence of a *package.json* file means that it uses *nodejs* as a runtime. Looking at the [package.json] file, other technologies or frameworks used in the project are:
