* Document your findings:

** Record any misconceptions you had
   - I said that:
    “Majority of the code lives in app.js”
   but it may or may not be true.
    app.js orchestrates application logic
    actual business logic is distributed across:
      models.js
      storage.js
      task_parser.js
      task_priority.js
      task_list_merge.js
   In healthy Node projects:
      app.js coordinates
      helper modules contain actual logic

   - I thought that Jest wasn't hooked up, because no single import from jest was in any of the test file.
     the A.I cleared the misconception by explaining that:
        Jest injects globals automatically. When Jest runs test files, it automatically provides:
        describe()
        test()
        it()
        expect()
        beforeEach()
        afterEach()
        jest.fn()

** Note important entry points and architectural patterns identified
   - CommonJS module system
   - File-based persistence
   - Layered separation of concerns
   - Unit + integration testing

** List the key components and their responsibilities
  CLI Layer
  (cli.js)
  ↓
  Application Layer
  (app.js)
  ↓
  Domain Logic
  (models.js, parser, priority, merge)
  ↓
  Persistence Layer
  (storage.js)
  ↓
  Filesystem
  (JSON/files)





